<h3>Spell Research</h3>

<p>
Vendors no longer carry all of your spells. You must begin to research some of
them. Yes, you're now playing a game that is assigning you homework.&nbsp; You'll need to buy an Elemental Grimoire from a vendor in your magician
guild. This book is a container into which you will place the components
required to make the spell you wish to research. Research is a lot like gambling.
When you click the combine button, the computer rolls the dice to
determine if you win - and get a copy of the spell, or lose - and do not. In
both cases the components vanish. The
percentages are in favor of the house. You're not the house.</p>

<p>
Each spell you wish to research requires a specific set of components. I won't
spoil the fun (?) of research for you, but in general you need 2 items dropped
off of monsters and 1 item you can purchase from a vendor. The monsters that
drop a spell are the level of the spell you're tying to make…or higher. That
means at level 16, you need to be killing level 16-19 (or so) mobs to get your
components. If you are soloing, you may not be able to kill such high level
mobs.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>You'll find a book with the recipes for research on the vendor that
sold you the Grimoire. However, the book will likely be in an ancient language.
You'll need to learn the language to read it.&nbsp; You can train languages from
your guild master.&nbsp; Other players can also teach you a language if they
know it.&nbsp; Save your training points for other things -- learn languages
from other players when possible.</p>

<p>
You can train research and make your own spells if you wish, or you can find a
higher-level magician to combine the spells for you. If you do this, don't
expect a magician to come halfway across the world to hit combine for you. And,
place the items in the book you want combined and then hand the book to the
higher-level magician when he or she is ready. That makes the combine much
faster. Another urban myth is that high level casters are penalized on low level
combines in order to force low-level casters to do their own research. I've seen
no evidence of that. Everything I've seen points to research being handled
exactly like a trade skill. A high level magician with a lot of skill can fail
to make a low level spell, just as a high level jeweler can fail at making a
relatively simple piece of jewelry. That's just normal randomness.</p>

<p>There are &quot;practice research&quot; items in the game.&nbsp; These are
items that can be combined to raise Research skill.&nbsp; Practice research
items are more difficult to come by than normal research items.</p>

<p>
Only magicians can research magician spells. And magicians cannot research the
spells of other classes.</p>

<h3>Strategy</h3>

<p>At level 4, your pet had very little hope of tanking a mob.&nbsp; However,
your pet is gaining strength fairly quickly.&nbsp; At this level, your pet can
hold off a mob on its own for longer than it could at level 4.&nbsp; This trend
will continue.&nbsp; At high levels, your pet can outright solo some mobs if you
need it to do so.&nbsp; This is as good a time as any to talk about &quot;pet
parking&quot; a mob.</p>

<p><u>Pet parking</u> is useful when you are grouped and get additional mobs on
a pull -- or a mob joins the fight and you can't deal with it right away.&nbsp;
As a group, you should decide in advance how adds will be handled.&nbsp; If you
have an enchanter, let the enchanter handle the adds.&nbsp; They are far better
equipped for it than are magicians.&nbsp; If you have more than one tank, one of
the tanks can handle an add if that's what the group chooses to do.&nbsp; A
player is much more intelligent about how to tank the add than your pet.&nbsp;
If your group has a class that can cast root, you may elect to root-park the
add.&nbsp; That is, pull the mob away from the group and root it out of melee
range.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>If you don't have an enchanter and you get an additional add, you can send your
pet to hold off the add for a short while.&nbsp; To pet park an add, just back
off your pet and then send the pet to attack the add. If the add is
hitting you, your pet will automatically attack once you've backed it off of the
one it was already fighting.</p>

<p>Note that the length of time your pet can hold off an add will grow as you
level.&nbsp; At this point, your pet isn't going to be able to hold off a mob
very long.&nbsp; Your pet should be damage-shielded and buffed to maximize the
effectiveness of pet parking.</p>

<h3>Phantom Leather</h3>

<p>At 16, you earn your first in a series of Phantom Armor spells.&nbsp; This
spell increases your AC a bit and gives you a faster health regen.&nbsp; It
requires a Cat's Eye Agate as a consumable component.&nbsp; (Remember to wear
your summoned necklace when casting this).&nbsp; This spell is overwritten by
certain buffs of other classes.&nbsp; It does not create the illusion of wearing
leather armor.</p>

<p>You'll find that certain shield spells of other classes will overwrite this
one.&nbsp; The cleric AC shield line overwrites the phantom armor series, for
example.&nbsp; This is annoying since phantom armor has a regen component, but
the cleric version does not.&nbsp; Also, you'll have to use more cats eye agate
to put the phantom armor up again.&nbsp; Make sure your group knows if you're
using phantom leather and do not want AC buffs.&nbsp; (Buffs that overwrite this
are typically pure AC buffs - the cleric Spirit Armor line.&nbsp; Cleric HP
series buffs will not overwrite your armor.)</p>

<p><i>Historical Note: The Phantom Series did not always have a regen component
to them.&nbsp; They used to simply boost a magician's AC.&nbsp; Although this
spell gave magicians the highest AC (when used in conjunction with the shielding
line of spells all casters get) it did not give magicians enough additional AC
to matter.&nbsp; The regeneration effect of this spell was a nice
addition.&nbsp; Especially since it stacks with regeneration spells cast by
Shaman and Druids.</i></p>

<h3>See Invisible</h3>

<p>No longer can other players (and in some cases, mobs) hide from your
eyes!&nbsp; Casting this will allow the target to see invisible beings.&nbsp;
You can cast this on yourself or others.&nbsp; If you are going to invis and
move as a group, casting this on everyone first is a good idea.</p>

<h3>Identify</h3>

<p>Some objects are not what they seem at first glance.&nbsp; This spell doesn't
have a lot of use in the game since nearly all objects are already
identified.&nbsp; Place an object on your mouse cursor, target yourself and
cast.&nbsp; The text name of the item will appear in your chat window.&nbsp; You
can also identify object someone else is holding on the cursor.&nbsp; Target the
other player and cast.&nbsp; This spell is useful for identifying a few quest
items.</p>

<h3>New Focus Item</h3>

<p>Summon Tiny Ring - when worn, this item will reduce the casting time of the
wearer's spells.</p>
